# {{project}}

A Turborepo monorepo for an Ontology SDK React component library, scaffolded with [`@osdk/create-app`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@osdk/create-app). Includes:

- **`apps/docs`** — Docusaurus docs site whose sidebar is grouped into _Getting Started_ (introduction, installation, project structure, the component generator, plus Blueprint and OSDK component references) and _Components_ (your own components). Each custom component page renders live with a code snippet and props table.
- **`packages/components`** — your own React components, consumed by the docs site and publishable to your Foundry npm registry.

## Quick start

```sh
npm install
npm run dev
```

The docs site listens on `http://localhost:3000`. In **Code Workspaces** (remote dev), `npm run dev:remote` binds Docusaurus to the port + base path the preview panel exposes (`DEV_SERVER_PORT` and `DEV_SERVER_BASE_PATH` env vars), so the preview iframe renders the docs directly.

Build everything: `npm run build`. The static docs bundle lands at `apps/docs/build`.

## Layout

```
apps/
  docs/        # Docusaurus 3 — the live preview surface
packages/
  components/  # your custom components (design-system-free)
.claude/
  skills/new-component/SKILL.md  # AI-driven component scaffolding
```

## Adding a component

In a Claude Code session, run:

```
/new-component
```

Claude asks for a name, the props (with TypeScript types), and a one-sentence description. It then writes the component (`packages/components/src/components/<Name>.tsx`), adds a named subpath export to `packages/components/package.json` (e.g. `./user-card` → the new file), generates an MDX docs page with a `<Playground>` whose controls are auto-derived from your prop types (text inputs for strings, sliders for ranges, switches for booleans, etc.), and patches `apps/docs/sidebars.ts`.

The skill prompt itself lives at `.claude/skills/new-component/SKILL.md` — open it to see (or tweak) the exact rules.

## Deploying the docs site

`npm run build` produces the static docs bundle at `apps/docs/build`. `create-app` generated a `foundry.config.json` at the repo root pointing `site.directory` at that folder, so you can deploy it to Foundry website hosting with:

```sh
export FOUNDRY_TOKEN=your-foundry-token
npx @osdk/cli site deploy
```

## Authentication

This docs site ships without any OAuth or OSDK client wiring. It renders your components and documentation as a static site, so it needs no Foundry login to view; when deployed, viewer access is gated by Foundry website hosting. `create-app` still generates `.env.*` and `.npmrc`, but nothing in the docs app reads the OAuth values today.

The OSDK components section (`ObjectTable`, `ActionForm`, and friends) is documentation-only for the same reason: rendering those live needs an authenticated client and a generated ontology SDK, which do not exist until your project has an ontology. To add live OSDK previews later, wire an OAuth client into `apps/docs/src/theme/Root.tsx` (client-side only) and generate your SDK.

## Publishing `@monorepo-app-placeholder/components`

`packages/components` is a normal npm package. Once it is published to your Foundry npm registry, another Foundry repo can install it via the **Libraries** panel in the IDE, or manually:

```sh
npm install @monorepo-app-placeholder/components
```

Adding a new package is just adding a new workspace under `packages/` (or letting the generator do it). Rename the `@monorepo-app-placeholder` scope to your own before publishing.

## Architecture notes

- Turbo handles task orchestration. `turbo run build` builds `packages/components` first, then the docs site.
- `tsconfig.base.json` is the shared baseline. Each project extends it with `composite`/`references` for incremental builds.
- Theming lives in `apps/docs/src/css/custom.css`; it sticks close to Docusaurus's stock Infima defaults and only styles the custom MDX components.
